{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6aec9c89-38d8-4494-901e-aba0e2db2d04","content":"It's a straightforward change. In your project file (or `Directory.Build.props`), simply **remove** (or set to `false`) the `UseVSTest` property:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Before -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n\n<!-- After -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n</Project>\n```\n\n**Why this is enough:** MSTest.Sdk 3.8+ uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform **by default**. The `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` flag was explicitly opting you back into the legacy runner. Removing it flips you to the new platform.\n\n**Key behavioral differences to be aware of:**\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **CLI** | Use `dotnet test` as before, but you can also run the test exe directly (`./MyTests.exe`) |\n| **Output** | Terminal output format changes (richer by default) |\n| **`.runsettings`** | Still supported, but platform-specific options use `--` CLI syntax (e.g. `--report-trx`) |\n| **TRX reports** | Add `<EnableMicrosoftTestingExtensionsCodeCoverage>true</EnableMicrosoftTestingExtensionsCodeCoverage>` or pass `--report-trx` if you need TRX output |\n| **CI filters** | `--filter` still works the same way |\n\nAfter the change, run `dotnet test` and verify your tests execute as expected.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5bc15e5a-e122-4627-8f93-559857c39c81","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The working directory appears to be empty. This is a general knowledge question about MSTest migration. Let me answer based on my knowledge.\n\nWith MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0 and `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>`, the user wants to switch to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (the newer test runner). Here's what they need to do:","outputTokens":497,"requestId":"3403:3387D:5215A35:5A42B54:69F3FB20"},"id":"22b75101-f200-4f6e-acbd-c5cdf4c4cdf2","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:00:28.853Z","parentId":"c73e15fd-08d5-455e-a6ae-775338fc8881"}
